#week-title("Two", "Setting Up the Circulation")

=== Core Teaching

The practical setup of a circulation requires more care than any previous
operation, because an error in sealing or in the vessel's configuration will
not be immediately visible — it may only become apparent weeks or months later
when the preparation is opened and found to have evaporated, leaked, or failed
to circulate correctly.

*Vessel options for the Initiate.* A true Pelican (a vessel with curved arms
returning condensed vapour to the body of the flask) can be constructed by a
glassblower or sourced from specialist laboratory suppliers. However, a
functioning circulation can also be achieved with common laboratory glassware:

- *Reflux condenser configuration:* A flask fitted with a water-cooled reflux
  condenser returns condensed vapour directly to the flask. This is a standard
  laboratory equivalent of the Pelican and is available from any laboratory
  supplier. The condenser water must be at a temperature low enough to fully
  condense the vapour before it reaches the flask neck.
- *Sealed flask digestion:* For preparations that circulate through diffusion
  rather than active evaporation and condensation — particularly mineral
  digestions at low heat — a well-sealed flask with sufficient headspace serves.
  The matter in the bottom of the flask is gently heated; the vapour collects
  at the top and, as the flask cools at night, condenses and returns. This
  operates on a natural diurnal rhythm.

*The choice of preparation.* The student selects a preparation suited to the
long work. Options at the Initiate level include:
- The Plant Stone from Year One (if still in progress under sealed digestion)
- The cohobated rainwater preparation from Year Two Month 1-3
- A new preparation of fermented plant material in a sealed vessel
- The border cohobation from Month 7, extended

Whatever is chosen, the preparation is sealed with the intention of not being
opened for a minimum of three months. This commitment is the operative
declaration that constitutes the beginning of the long work.

#lab[
  *Circulation Setup Protocol*
  + *Select and clean the vessel* thoroughly. No residue from a previous
    preparation should remain.
  + *Charge the vessel* no more than one-third full, to allow adequate headspace
    for vapour movement.
  + *Seal all joints* with appropriate luting (clay and sand paste, or PTFE
    tape for ground glass joints). Check each joint by sight and by smell —
    if you can detect the preparation's scent from outside the vessel, the
    seal is insufficient.
  + *Label the vessel* with: contents, date sealed, preparation type, intended
    minimum circulation period.
  + *Set heat source* to maintain steady warmth. A temperature-regulated heating
    mat, a seed propagator, or a warm water bath all serve for low-temperature
    circulations.
  + *First check at 48 hours:* observe without opening. Is the vessel sweating
    (condensation forming on the glass above the liquid level)? Is the rhythm
    of vapour movement visible?
  + *Record in the long-work log:* a separate section of the laboratory journal
    dedicated to observations of the circulating preparation at each weekly check.
]

=== Topics This Week

- Vessel options: Pelican, reflux condenser, sealed flask
- Choosing the preparation for the long work
- Sealing protocol: luting, checking, the smell test
- The long-work log: dedicated observation records

#inner-work[
  *The Commitment*

  Before sealing the circulation vessel, sit with it for ten minutes. Hold the
  sealed flask (or the flask as it will be when sealed) and ask honestly: am I
  willing to give this preparation at least three months of consistent attention
  without opening it or altering it?

  Write one paragraph in your inner work journal as a declaration of this
  commitment. Date it. This is the inner equivalent of sealing the vessel.
]

